    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** - May 26, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🛢️ The ceasefire got air quotes\n\nWashington and Tehran are apparently negotiating nicely, in the special diplomatic sense that includes fresh U.S. strikes.\n\n- **The action:** U.S. Central Command said it carried out self-defense strikes in southern Iran, including missile launch sites and boats placing mines.\n- **The contradiction:** Trump said talks were proceeding nicely while AP described the strikes as the latest blow to a weekslong ceasefire around the Iran war.\n- **The pressure point:** Hormuz remains effectively under Iranian chokehold, disrupting a route that once carried about a fifth of traded crude oil and natural gas.\n\n*The deal is alive, if one defines alive as still requiring air cover.*\n\n**Sources:** [AP](https://apnews.com/article/01a13e9a63ece786a0a7fa4933dbf09b) | [AP Markets](https://apnews.com/article/71cc7b49f2ca3462a118878c93c75940)\n\n---\n\n## 🚀 Pyongyang warmed up the neighborhood\n\nNorth Korea waited for Russia and China to complain about Western pressure, then contributed a small ballistic footnote.\n\n- **The launch:** South Korea's military said North Korea fired a close-range ballistic missile from Jongju toward the sea on May 26.\n- **The distance:** the missile flew about 80 kilometers, while other projectiles, reportedly including multiple rocket launch systems, were fired at the same time.\n- **The signal:** it was North Korea's first weapons launch event since April 19, when state media described short-range missile tests with cluster bomb warheads.\n\n*Subtlety remains unavailable on the Korean Peninsula.*\n\n**Sources:** [AP](https://apnews.com/article/060148d7789377ff8691bc24d42b136d)"
  }
